DIV1.P:
The Poet having thus exhausted imagination as well as mythology, in the description of punish∣ments for the disturbers of mankind and foes to their country, raises his conclusion to a height of horror beyond the reach of expression—

"Had I a hundred mouths, a hundred tongues,

"A voice of brass, and adamantine lungs;

"Not half the mighty scene could I disclose;

"Repeat their  their dreadful woes.

Nor has Virgil strayed any farther through the fields of fancy or fable in this place, than to bor∣row strength of colouring for the garb of truth; and I suspect, that he drank from a purer fountain than that of Helicon, when he peopled his Tartarus with the ancient scourges of the human race. An au∣thority sacred among christians has indeed given us a most awful confirmation of his doctrine.
